title: For Sale/Trade:  Mauser 98K (BCD 4 code, Sauer)
postcontent: For Sale: BCD 4 code Mauser 98K rifle assembled by JP Sauer & Sohn. I believe the block to be an N or V, but you can judge for yourself based on the photos. I also have an original sling and ASW 42 wood gripped bayonet with scabbard and frog that all match the rifle nicely that I will offer to the buyer at prices below retail. The sling shown in photos is a repro and not is included.Condition: Rifle is not import marked. All serial numbered parts that are on the rifle are matching with the exception of the firing pin which bears a 3443 serial and 280 proof mark. The triggerguard is an unnumbered stamped BYF / 135 proof marked piece with a serial numbered milled floorplate which is correct for this rifle. The rifle had an earlier milled H style upper band installed when I originally purchased it and I have since replaced it with a stamped band. The band matches well, but has an extra hole on the left side as it is likely off of an Israeli rifle. I had planned to locate a more correct replacement stamped and welded band without any markings or serial numbers, but have not done so at this time (there is a seller on eBay that sells unmarked replacement bands for $39 plus shipping). Other noteable items are a missing cleaning rod and bayonet lug pin, a thin delamination crack in the tang area of the stock, and the fact that the handguard has been bedded to the barrel with clear epoxy. The crack is a common issue with the laminated 98K stocks and it does not penetrate down into the wrist. It should be easily repairable if needed. I will just leave that decision up to the next owner. There does not appear to be any setback at the recoil lug so the rifle should be in fireable condition as-is. In regards to the handguard, it's underside has been partially coated with clear epoxy and bedded to the barrel. I am assuming that this was done due to the handguard previously being loose. This issue isn't noticeable until the handguard is removed. Both the stock and the handguard are serial number matching to the rifle and there is a faint Heer stamp on the stock. Buttplate is unmarked and bears a JVD ink stamp on the preservative paint coating the interior. Bore does not exhibit much wear. It is clean and shiney, but does have a couple areas of pitting, mainly in the throat area of the barrel.All matching, non-import marked BCD 4 code Sauer rifles are bringing $1400-$1500+ so I have tried my best to price the rifle accordingly based on condition noted above.For additional photos, please copy and paste the following address into your browser: http://imgur.com/a/179YYCall or text REDACTED for more information.

title: For Sale/Trade:  25-45 Sharps AR-15 custom build
postcontent:
This is a custom AR15 chambered in 25-45 Sharps. It comes with everything on the list below, plus a soft tactical case with enough pockets to carry it all. The cartridge is the same as a .223 only necked up to fit a 25 cal. round, therefore you can use your existing .223/5.56 magazines, and it makes it legal to hunt with even in those states that don’t allow a .223.
For those not familiar with this cartridge, here you go: The 25-45 SHARPS cartridge was developed by SRC to maximize the performance of the Modern Sporting Rifle (MSR) platform. With a greater muzzle velocity and harder hitting 70 87 and 100 grain bullets, it’s performance surpasses the .223 REM/5.56 NATO. The 25-45 SHARPS is compatible with existing .223/5.56 bolt carrier groups and magazines available for the MSR platform.
